he "enforced disappearance" of thousands of Chileans and an unknown number of foreign nationals. Ensalaco spent five years in Chile investigating the impact of Pinochet's rule and interviewing members of the truth commission created to investigate the human rights violations under Pinochet. The political objective of human rights organizations, Ensalaco contends, is to bring sufficient pressure to bear on violent regimes to induce them to end policies of repression. However, these efforts are severely limited by the disparities of power between human rights organizations and regimes intent on ruthlessly eliminating dissent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDisappeared personszChile. 0aHuman rightszChilexHistory. 0aMilitary governmentzChilexHistory. 0aPolitical persecutionzChile. 0aVictims of state-sponsored terrorismzChile. 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220186440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812201864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812201864.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041352-6  Penn Press eBook Package Law & Political Science  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eB